And it is hardly necessary to observe that, while the monks could do what was necessary ¹in the way of embankment, 01· what not, on their own side, on the other they were powerless, apart from the special permission of the possessor, and the privilege accorded by him of raising the necessary embank- ments, wherever needed, on his side also.
